<section xml:id="section-TFSC">
    <title>Misc Ancient Greek Mathematics (WIP)</title>

    \begin{itemize}
        \item Numbers like $\pi$ and $\sqrt{2}$ were not thought of as numbers but as magnitudes. Believed in numbers as proportions, either whole numbers or ratios of whole numbers (rational numbers).
        \item Avoided negative numbers, because of their reliance on geometry (you can't have negative length, or area).
        \item Infinity was thought of as potential infinity, not actual infinity. Infinity was a process of indefinite continuation, rather than eventual completion. For example, you could form the sequence of natural numbers $1, 2, 3, \dots$ by indefinitely adding 1. However, there was not an idea of the set of all natural numbers $\mathbb{N}$.
        \item Believed infinity was problematic.
        \item Their rejection of irrational numbers were due to their rejection of infinite processes.
        \item Developed a theory of proportions, which has parallels with modern real analysis and Dedekind cuts.
        \item The Greek perspective on infinity was believed by mathematicians up to Euler, Newton, Gauss, etc.
        \item Only in the 1900s, did infinity have a modern treatment.
        \item Used infinite series, but avoided actual infinity.
    \end{itemize}
</section>